	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Fri Oct 18, 2013 9:08 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Developing a game for NES and Game Boy possible?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">slobu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Couldn't you just use C with the system specific stuff parceled out?</div><br />The problem is that AFAIK there isn't a C compiler that targets both the 6502 and the GBZ80, so the peculiarities of each compiler would most likely prevent you from sharing the same source files.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Also, what's wrong with writing 2 different hardware specific game engines that both use mostly the same game data?</div><br />That seems like the way to go, but even then each CPU has a different way of optimally addressing data, so you might benefit from reorganizing the data into formats that best fit each CPU as opposed to simply .incbin'ing the raw data.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


